text.tspan: unique passwords per site made easy.

flowRoot.flowPara: Why? Hashpash makes it easier to maintain a better password strategy. That is: unique passwords for each and every site. That's important as we've seen more and more database dumps of websites containing all the user's password in an easy to read format for those who hacked it.
How? Hashpash hashes your password with the sitename. You'll be using the resulting mash to use as the password for that particular site.

Secure? Nothing is sent to a remote server (hence nothing is being stored). The technology to hash your password (SHA-2) can't be reversed computationally, but it is still prone to dictionary attacks, although even that is hash.
Can it be even more secure? Yep, but with increasing the risk of loosing your password.
